OK so `ManagedServiceIdentityTypeConverter` is internal in this project. I can call the converter directly:

For serialize (line 31):
```csharp
// Before:
JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions);
// After - call converter directly:new ManagedServiceIdentityType.ManagedServiceIdentityTypeConverter().Write(writer, ManagedServiceIdentityType, jOptions ?? new JsonSerializerOptions());
```

For deserialize (line 206):
```csharp
// Before:
type = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<ManagedServiceIdentityType>($"{{{property}}}");


// After - call converter directly:
var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes($"{{{property}}}");
var reader = new Utf8JsonReader(bytes);
reader.Read();
type = new ManagedServiceIdentityType.ManagedServiceIdentityTypeConverter().Read(ref reader, typeof(ManagedServiceIdentityType), jOptions ?? new JsonSerializerOptions());
```

I notice the `DeserializeManagedServiceIdentity` method already has a `jOptions` parameter available, so I can pass that directly to the converter instead of creating a new instance.

For the `UserAssignedIdentity` deserialization, I need to replace the inline `JsonSerializer.Deserialize` call with a call to the static `DeserializeUserAssignedIdentity` method, passing the property value and options through properly. Checking the WriteObjectValue method signature to confirm it'll work with UserAssignedIdentity since it implements IJsonModel, and the foreach loop iterates over a dictionary where the values are definitely UserAssignedIdentity objects.

